: "PERSONALITY TRAIT DOMAINS"}, {"i": 207, "t": "6D11"}, {"i": 208, "t": "BORDERLINE PATTERN"}, {"i": 209, "t": "6D10.2"}, {"i": 210, "t": "ANTISOCIAL/DISSOCIAL PERSONALITY DISORDER"}, {"i": 211, "t": "6D10"}, {"i": 212, "t": "ICD-10 CATEGORIES TRANSITION TO ICD-11"}, {"i": 213, "t": "6D30–6D3Z"}, {"i": 214, "t": "PARAPHILIC DISORDERS"}, {"i": 215, "t": "Expand/collapse"}, {"i": 216, "t": "6D31"}, {"i": 217, "t": "6D36"}, {"i": 218, "t": "PEDOPHILIC DISORDER"}, {"i": 219, "t": "6D50–6D51"}, {"i": 220, "t": "FACTITIOUS DISORDERS"}, {"i": 221, "t": "Expand/collapse"}, {"i": 222, "t": "6D50"}, {"i": 223, "t": "FACTITIOUS DISORDER IMPOSED ON SELF (MUNCHAUSEN SYNDROME)"}, {"i": 224, "t": "6D51"}, {"i": 225, "t": "FACTITIOUS DISORDER IMPOSED ON ANOTHER"}, {"i": 226, "t": "6D70–6D8Z"}, {"i": 227, "t": "NEUROCOGNITIVE DISORDERS"}, {"i": 228, "t": "Expand/collapse"}, {"i": 229, "t": "6D75"}, {"i": 230, "t": "DELIRIUM"}, {"i": 231, "t": "6D71"}, {"i": 232, "t": "LIGHT NEUROCOGNITIVE DISORDER (LIGHT COGNITIVE DISORDER, MCI)"}, {"i": 233, "t": "6D70"}, {"i": 234, "t": "DEMENTIA — GENERAL PRINCIPLES"}, {"i": 235, "t": "6D70"}, {"i": 236, "t": "DEMENTIA DUE TO ALZHEIMER DISEASE"}, {"i": 237, "t": "6E20"}, {"i": 238, "t": "MENTAL DISORDERS RELATED TO PREGNANCY AND POSTPARTUM PERIOD"}, {"i": 239, "t": "Expand/collapse"}, {"i": 240, "t": "6E20"}, {"i": 241, "t": "MENTAL DISORDERS DURING PREGNANCY (PERINATAL DEPRESSION/PSYCHOSIS)"}, {"i": 242, "t": "6E20.0"}, {"i": 243, "t": " EARLY POST-PARTUM EMOTIONAL REACTION (\"Baby blues\")"}, {"i": 244, "t": "6E20"}, {"i": 245, "t": "POSTPARTUM DEPRESSION (PPD)"}, {"i": 246, "t": "6E21"}, {"i": 247, "t": "POSTPARTUM PSYCHOSIS (PPP)"}, {"i": 248, "t": "6E20"}, {"i": 249, "t": "POSTPARTUM ANXIETY, OCD, PTSD"}, {"i": 250, "t": "6E40"}, {"i": 251, "t": "PSYCHOSOMATIC FACTORS"}, {"i": 252, "t": "6E60–6E6Z"}, {"i": 253, "t": "SECONDARY PSYCHIC AND BEHAVIORAL SYNDROMES"}, {"i": 254, "t": "7A00–7B2Z"}, {"i": 255, "t": "SLEEP DISORDERS"}, {"i": 256, "t": "HA00–HA8Z"}, {"i": 257, "t": "SEXUAL DYSFUNCTIONS AND SEXUAL HEALTH DISORDERS"}, {"i": 258, "t": "FINAL RECOMMENDATIONS"}, {"i": 259, "t": "Practical meeting for clinicians."}, {"i": 260, "t": "Key clinical lessons derived from all chapters of the book:"}, {"i": 261, "t": "Diagnosis is always the second step, not the first"}, {"i": 262, "t": "Before diagnosing a mental disorder, always:"}, {"i": 263, "t": "Exclude medical causes."}, {"i": 264, "t": "– particularly new onset after age 40–50, acute presentation, atypical profile, somatic symptoms, hormonal period changes;"}, {"i": 265, "t": "Check substance use"}, {"i": 266, "t": "– covert substance component in 30% of each case;"}, {"i": 267, "t": "Ask trauma history with open questions"}, {"i": 268, "t": "– complex PTSD and personality disorders are often the result of trauma, but trauma history does not emerge without screening."}, {"i": 269, "t": "WHO, 2019, implementation 2022 — ICD-11 'primary vs secondary' principle — the main framework for clinicians."}, {"i": 270, "t": "Psychotherapy – first choice in most cases"}, {"i": 271, "t": "WHO, 2019, implementation 2022 — central message of the ICD-11 era:"}, {"i": 272, "t": "Psychotherapy effectiveness is confirmed, at least equal to pharmacotherapy, superior in many disorders:"}, {"i": 273, "t": "Mild-moderate depression."}, {"i": 274, "t": "– CBT, IPT equivalent to SSRIs;"}, {"i": 275, "t": "In anxiety disorders"}, {"i": 276, "t": "– CBT first-line;"}, {"i": 277, "t": "In OCD"}, {"i": 278, "t": "– ERP essential for OCD; SSRIs adjunctive;"}, {"i": 279, "t": "In PTSD"}, {"i": 280, "t": "– TF-CBT, EMDR first-line;"}, {"i": 281, "t": "Personality Disorders"}, {"i": 282, "t": "– DBT, MBT, TFP – more effective than pharmacotherapy;"}, {"i": 283, "t": "In eating disorders"}, {"i": 284, "t": "– CBT-E, FBT;"}, {"i": 285, "t": "In childhood behavioral disorders"}, {"i": 286, "t": "– parent education programs."}, {"i": 287, "t": "Farmakoterapiya"}, {"i": 288, "t": "In many cases, adjunct therapy helps to enhance and maintain the effectiveness of psychotherapy for the patient."}, {"i": 289, "t": "Principle of minimum effective dose"}, {"i": 290, "t": "Start low, increase slowly"}, {"i": 291, "t": "The patient has reached the definitive minimal effective dose."}, {"i": 292, "t": "Avoid excessive polypharmacy"}, {"i": 293, "t": "– especially in elderly, in comorbidity, in personality disorders;"}, {"i": 294, "t": "Discontinuation or reduction of medication"}, {"i": 295, "t": "It requires caution - abrupt discontinuation of SSRIs is not possible; benzodiazepines should be gradually tapered."}, {"i": 296, "t": "Working with culture and context"}, {"i": 297, "t": "In the Azerbaijani context:"}, {"i": 298, "t": "Somatic presentation"}, {"i": 299, "t": "Widespread – depression and anxiety screening is required in primary care;"}, {"i": 300, "t": "Stigma and isolation"}, {"i": 301, "t": "– psychiatrist visit is concealed; working in primary care or internal medicine base is effective;"}, {"i": 302, "t": "Family system is strong"}, {"i": 303, "t": "– family involvement in treatment is a major resource;"}, {"i": 304, "t": "Religious and cultural beliefs"}, {"i": 305, "t": "– should be considered, but to avoid pathological subject;"}, {"i": 306, "t": "Karabakh War veterans"}, {"i": 307, "t": "– PTSD, cPTSD, high need for trauma-focused intervention."}, {"i": 308, "t": "Screening should be standard in primary care"}, {"i": 309, "t": "The main screening tools should be routinely applied in primary care:"}, {"i": 310, "t": "PHQ-9"}, {"i": 311, "t": "– depression (at every medical visit);"}, {"i": 312, "t": "GAD-7"}, {"i": 313, "t": "– anxiety;"}, {"i": 314, "t": "AUDIT"}, {"i": 315, "t": "– alcohol use;"}, {"i": 316, "t": "EPDS"}, {"i": 317, "t": "– perinatal women;"}]